  <h1>What to Do After a Rideshare Accident</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>1. Document the driver&rsquo;s app status</h2><p>If you are a passenger, screenshot the Uber/Lyft app showing the active ride. If you are a third party, ask the driver for their app status or look for the rideshare trade dress on the vehicle. The driver&rsquo;s app status determines which insurance phase applies — the most important fact in your case.</p>
  <h2>2. Get medical care</h2><p>Even if you feel okay, get evaluated. Rideshare accidents can involve significant impact forces. Adrenaline masks pain. Medical records from the day of the accident document the injury&rsquo;s onset.</p>
  <h2>3. Report through the app</h2><p>Use the Uber or Lyft app to report the accident immediately. Both companies have in-app reporting features. This creates a record and triggers the claims process. Also call 911 and get a police report.</p>
  <h2>4. Collect information</h2><p>Driver&rsquo;s name, license plate, insurance information, and rideshare company. Names and numbers of all witnesses. Photographs of vehicles, injuries, and the scene. Check whether nearby businesses have surveillance cameras.</p>
  <h2>5. Consult a rideshare accident attorney</h2><p>Rideshare claims involve multiple insurers and complex coverage questions. An experienced attorney navigates the phases, ensures the correct limits are applied, and coordinates multi-party claims. Most work on contingency.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-rideshare-accident-claims-work">how rideshare claims work</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
